Object Display:

#) How to Display JavaScript Objects?
    - Displaying a JavaScript object will output [object Object].

        const person = {
            name: "John",
            age: 30,
            city: "Nepal"
        };
        let text = person;
        document.getElementById("1").innerHTML = `Displaying object person: ${text}`;
        // Displaying object person: [object Object]

#) Why do I See [object Object]?
    - [Object Object] appears when you try to put an object (a data structure with properties)
        into a context where a string is expected.
    - Some solutions to display JavaScript objects are:
        -> Displaying the Object Properties by name
        -> Displaying the Object Properties in a Loop
        -> Displaying the Object using Object.values()
        -> Displaying the Object using JSON.stringify()


1) Displaying Object Properties:
        
        const person = {
            name: "John",
            age: 30,
            city: "Nepal"
        };
        let text1 = `${person.name}, ${person.age}, ${person.age}`;
        document.getElementById("2").innerHTML = text1;

        o/p: John, 30, Nepal


2) Using a For .. In Loop:
    - The properties of an object can be collected in a loop:
        
        const person = {
            name: "John",
            age: 30,
            city: "Nepal"
        };
        let text2 = "";
        for(const key in person) {
            text2 += person[key] + " ";
        }
        document.getElementById("3").innerHTML = text2

        o/p: John 30 Nepal


3) Using Object.values():
    - Object.values() creates an array from the property values:

        const person = {
            name: "John",
            age: 30,
            city: "Nepal"
        };
        // create an array
        const personArray = Object.values(person);
        // stringify the array
        let text3 = personArray.toString();
        document.getElementById("4").innerHTML = text3;

        o/p: John,30,Nepal

    ⚠️ we create an array of values in the object. In the same way we can create array of keys 
        
        const personArray = Object.keys(person);    // name,age,city


4) Using Object.entries():
    - Object.entries() makes it simple to use objects in loops:

        const person = {
            name: "John",
            age: 30,
            city: "Nepal"
        };
        let text4 = "";
        for(let [key, value] of Object.entries(person)) {
            text4 += `${key}: ${value} <br>`;
        }
        document.getElementById("5").innerHTML = text4;

        o/p:    name: John
                age: 30
                city: Nepal


5) Using JSON.stringify():
    - JavaScript objects can be converted to a string with JSON method JSON.stringify().
    - JSON.stringify() is included in JavaScript and supported in all browsers.

        const person = {
            name: "John",
            age: 30,
            city: "Nepal"
        };
        let text5 = JSON.stringify(person);
        document.getElementById("6").innerHTML = text5;

        o/p: {"name":"John","age":30,"city":"Nepal"}